I experimented around (75 upscales) to find these settings and methods. This uses a transformer, my [4xRealWebPhoto_v4_dat2](https://github.com/Phhofm/models/releases/tag/4xRealWebPhoto_v4_dat2) model, for accuracy and consistency and restoration. Then SUPIR to improve the results a little bit more on degraded input that is too much for my model to handle.

These settings keep SUPIR pretty restricted meaning it enforces consistency on SUPIR because diffusion based models that use the latent space for upscales normally change the input too much, which I rather call 'img2img enlarger' or 'img2img enhancer', than super resolution of the original.

But if the input is too degraded, you can of course play around with these settings and allow for a little bit more leeway for restoration.

Settings:

Seed: 919117296619733 (other manual seeds end up in too noisy output. But can be tested out or set to random. But if doing tests, why not just keep this manual)

Checkpoint: [V9+RDPhoto2-Lightning_4S](https://civitai.com/models/133005/juggernaut-xl)

10 Steps
CFG 3
ETA 1.5
All others set to 1, except restore to -1


Notes
Did not see difference between restore 1 and -1
Did not see much difference between churn 1 and 2
Steps 10 is enough, more takes longer without giving way more improvement (tradeoff)
You can increase cfg or decrease eta or 
 - you can change eta and cfg to adapt to image, lower eta or increase cfg or decrease control scale if these are not enough. But best just leave at these defaults since like i said, i am not a fan of diffusion based changing too much (its a different image then) 
Did 75 upscale tests

takes too long using moondream for the prompt, so using we14 tagger with wd-v1-4-convnextv2-tagger-v2 (I tested all these versions, the default one gave me no_humans tag where there were humans so that made them all into metallic sculptures or something, looked very bad)

Used lightning checkpoint for faster upscales.

Previews is so i see and understand everything, but you can delete if you want. If you have more vram than me (16gb) you can also keep models loaded for faster consequent upscales. VRAM just needs to be enough so it can do the transformer upscale, then wd14, then supir, if you want to keep them loaded.

Use ColorMatch at the beginning, in case there is a color shift in the upscaling model already, and at the end, in case of SUPIR doing something funky, but at the end i seldomly saw colors not matching so maybe not needed at the end. Use nearest-exact for color matching.

I also tested, using my transformer model instead of a simply lanczos upscale gave more accurate results to the input.
